## The 2.5ct Lab Crossover: Why Natural Beats Lab at This Weight

Every post in this oval series has discussed the lab alternative. At 1ct, lab saved $300. At 1.5ct, $6,900. At 2ct, $15,453. The savings grew at every weight.

At 2.5ct, the pattern reverses.

The only 2.5ct lab oval currently available on Blue Nile is the [IGI 2.50ct G-VVS2 at $30,096](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28940937?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Compare that to the natural G-VS2 at $27,683. The lab stone costs **$2,413 more than the natural stone** — and it's only G-VVS2, not D-IF like the lab advantages at smaller weights.

This is **The 2.5ct Lab Crossover** — the weight at which lab-grown ovals lose their price advantage over natural alternatives. It happens because:

1. **Lab production of 2.5ct+ ovals is harder and less standardized** than at 1ct–2ct. Fewer producers, less competition, higher per-stone cost.
2. **Natural inventory at 2.5ct is thinner**, but demand is also lower — fewer buyers shop this size, which keeps pricing from reaching the extremes that create the lab gap.
3. **The lab premium for larger stones** reflects the genuine difficulty of growing high-quality rough at 2.5ct+.

The practical implication: **buy natural at 2.5ct.** The [G-VS2 at $27,683](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28232926?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is a better stone at a lower price than the only lab alternative. The lab calculus that dominated the 1ct–2ct range does not apply here.

